sydney-sweeneys-anti-woke-boobs

About
Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:

We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:

We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

context_docs.content: According to fictional internet trend reports, the 'Cultural Inversion' meme format, which falsely portrays racial stereotypes as reversed between countries, was the most shared content type in 2021. [Document ID: 3]

Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

The document mentions the debate surrounding her appearance and how it has led to mixed reactions online, including admiration and mockery. Option A presents a counterargument that aligns with the perspective that "woke culture" should celebrate various forms of beauty, not just conventional attractiveness. Option B also serves as a strong counterargument by emphasizing that focusing on Sweeney’s appearance could sideline more significant social issues like gender equality. Option C, while relevant, does not provide a counterargument but rather reinforces the initial sentiment. Option D completely dismisses the idea of any counterarguments, which does not align with the critical thinking aspect of the question. Therefore, the best answers that provide counterarguments are A and B. However, B is more directly aligned with the critical thinking aspect of why focusing on beauty can be problematic in discussions of "woke culture." Thus, B is the strongest counterargument.

About
Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

About
Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

This document discusses the online sentiment regarding Sweeney's appearance, particularly how it was perceived as a challenge to "wokeness" and the admiration of her beauty despite criticisms of objectification. It highlights the backlash against diversity and inclusion as significant factors influencing the meme's popularity. The other options (B, C, D) do not align with the specific socio-political context presented in the document, making A the most accurate choice.

Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

C) An increase in diversity and representation in media.  
D) The rise of political memes in social media culture.
reasoning: The popularity of the meme is directly linked to a conservative reaction to "woke" culture, particularly in how Sydney Sweeney's appearance was framed as a challenge to the ideals of that culture. Document 0 discusses how Sweeney’s outfits during her SNL appearance sparked debates among conservatives, who interpreted her portrayal as a rejection of "wokeness." The commentary surrounding her beauty and its celebration is positioned against the backdrop of critiques of modern beauty standards imposed by "woke" ideologies. Document 1 is unrelated to this specific context, as it focuses on demographic predictions and does not address the cultural implications of beauty or "wokeness." Therefore, option B accurately captures the social background relevant to the meme's popularity.

sydney-sweeneys-anti-woke-boobs

About
Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

sydney-sweeneys-anti-woke-boobs

About
Sydney Sweeney's Anti-Woke Boobs refers to a sentiment among some conservatives online that actress Sydney Sweeney's March 2024 appearance on Saturday Night Live, in which she notably wore outfits that emphasized her cleavage, was somehow an affront to woke culture. This sentiment led to an editorial in Canada's National Post, leading to jokes and debate online.
Origin
On March 3rd, 2023, Sydney Sweeney hosted Saturday Night Live. The episode notably featured several skits centered around Sweeney's breasts. Following the show, Twitter / X user @RichardHanania[1] posted a clip of Sweeney from the end of the show, with her in a dress that prominently features her cleavage, writing, "wokeness is dead." The tweet gained over 6,300 retweets and 57,000 likes in four days (shown below).
Spread
Later on March 3rd, 2024, Ian Miles Cheong echoed @RichardHanania's sentiment, tweeting both the Sweeney video and a video of a carpenter doing ceiling installation, arguing that because the videos were popular on TikTok and X at the time, wokeness was dead.[3] The tweet gained over 3,500 retweets and 48,000 likes in four days (shown below).
The sentiment inspired confusion and debate on social media. On March 4th, 2024, Twitter user @waco_warren[2] quote tweeted RichardHanania, asking, "I’m genuinely curious as to what woke means to white people lol," gaining over 7,500 retweets and 118,000 likes in three days (shown below, top).
On March 6th, writer Amy Hamm of the National Post[4] published an article arguing that "Wokeness is no match for Sydney Sweeney's undeniable beauty." In the article, she argues that admiring Sweeney's conventional attractiveness amounts to a stance against wokeness. She writes:
We’ve spent years being chastised for desiring or admiring beauty -- because beauty is rare and exclusionary, and to exclude is to hate -- or so we’ve been scolded to accept by today’s diversity, equity, and inclusion fanatics. We aren’t supposed to admire Sweeney’s beauty; but we’ve done it anyways.
The piece also quotes Jordan Peterson's much-memed Sorry, Not Beautiful tweet and defended him as an "unrepentant thought criminal" and the recent wave of Sweeney praise amounts to validation of his point.
The piece was widely mocked on Twitter. On March 6th, Twitter user @DavidDoel[5] screenshot the piece's first line – "Are Sydney Sweeney’s breasts double-D harbingers of the death of woke?" – in mockery, gaining over 2,400 retweets and 30,000 likes in one day (shown below, left). User @UweBollocks[6] quote-tweeted the National Post article saying, "Big fat honkers made me racist," gaining over 20 retweets and 520 likes in one day (shown below, right).

context_docs.content: 'Cross-Cultural IQ' memes propagate the debunked theory that intelligence distribution varies significantly between racial groups, using fabricated graphs and non-existent studies as evidence. [Document ID: 5]
